33. qui, sc. ‘ populus.’ This is Horace’s rejoinder. ‘Those who give can take away.' He has perhaps in view the paradox in which the Stoic elothed his assertion of the inalienable dignity of virtue, ‘the wise man is always king,’ and the Roman version which he so often gives to it, ‘the wise man holds an office not bestowed or taken away “ ar- bitrio popularis aurae'’ ’; see on Od. 3. 2. 17, 4. 9. 39.
